About

The area

Neighborhood: Downtown Dubai
You can’t fail to miss Dubai’s iconic Burj Khalifa, the world’s tallest building. It towers over the city and resides in the prestigious Downtown development. Once an old army base, Downtown is now the jewel in Dubai’s crown, a beautiful residential and leisure area housing not only the world’s tallest building, but the world’s largest fountains and mall. Wide marble sidewalks are perfect for strolling, with restaurants, art galleries and children’s play areas. Specially commissioned sculptures line the roads and Downtown is often used as a canvas for modern art displays and community events such as Classic Car Shows and National Day parades. In the cooler months, cross one of the many bridges to the Burj Khalifa park and enjoy a picnic alongside residents and visitors, or enjoy a lunch or dinner watch the dancing fountains. Because of its mixed use, Downtown is a fantastic place to mix with Dubai residents and locals and watch real life unfold in a cosmopolitan environment.

  • Burj Khalifa/Dubai Mall • 10 min walk

  • Deanosaur89
    Edmonton, Canada8,742 contributions
    Sunrise Experience for the Wallet
    Going up the Burj Khalifa can be pricey depending on the date and time so the Sunrise + Morning Treat Package was something we chose to save some money. To get to the At the Top area we went to the Fashion Avenue entrance by Cartier at Dubai Mall. The security will open doors for Dubai Mall before 5:30 am and our entrance opened around 5:15 am but we saw people who had gotten up there earlier. Getting here early meant we got an elevator all to ourselves but if we had to wait there were enough things to look at and read in an exhibition hall before the elevator. The Sunrise experience only gets you access to the 124rth floor but there's a nice terrace and we got a pretty good sunrise. You can stay here as long as you want and many people were camping out in the window frames for the viewing spots. Outside of the terrace there's not much - there is a gift shop, a cafe, bathrooms and some TVs displaying facts and statistics about the Burj Khalifa. The gift shop is underwhelming and the cafe was closed while we were up there. There are other ticket packages but they can get expensive so do your research and choose what you'd like. The queue to get down wasn't managed well and people were crowding the elevators that go up and down. We felt they could have used a couple of staff to let people know where to wait to go down so that people could disembark the elevators more easily and the area didn't get too crowded. We felt people were pushy to get in the elevators so we had to wait a bit even though we were one of the first to get line up to go down. The treat at the cafe was nice and you had a choice between several hot and cold beverages including coffee, tea, hot chocolate and juice with many options for each. The treat also included a pastry and we had cheese puffs, chicken puffs and some sort of cheese/chicken pie to choose from. A big perk for us getting here so early was that we got unobstructed pictures near the Dubai Fountains of the Burj Khalifa after we came down and they were perfect. It does not matter which ticket package you buy but it is recommended to purchase in advance. At the Top is located in Dubai Mall near a food court and the signage is very helpful to lead the way. To get here you could use the Burj Khalifa/Dubai Mall metro station which is about a 15-20 minute walk but it is covered and air conditioned.
    Visited November 2023
    Traveled as a couple
    Written November 18, 2023
